Below is an example of some code I wrote for a data challenge using a public and well-known dataset.

Breast Cancer Cell Detection

Develop a model that predicts whether a biopsied breast tumor is benign (not harmful) or malignant (cancerous), given a set of attributes about the tumor.

The dataset consists of 699 cells for which you have the following features:

Sample code number: id number Clump Thickness: 1 - 10 Uniformity of Cell Size: 1 - 10 Uniformity of Cell Shape: 1 - 10 Marginal Adhesion: 1 - 10 Single Epithelial Cell Size: 1 - 10 Bare Nuclei: 1 - 10 Bland Chromatin: 1 - 10 Normal Nucleoli: 1 - 10 Mitoses: 1 - 10

Class: (2 for benign, 4 for malignant)

The dataset is also available here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.data I hunted down the original paper here: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC55130/pdf/pnas01048-0130.pdf

Overal goals

  • I need to build a binary classifer.
  • I will optimize for recall since this seems to be a screening tool (i.e. I would suggest this product be run as a first pass to prioritize which samples a physician should look at).
  • I will extract feature importance and do feature reduction to reduce time and money to collect each feature

There are various ways to do this: sklearn has several methods...KNNimputter seems like it would work well here since its multi-dimensional data and doesn't appear to be missing at random.

def predict_and_eval_classification_perf(model_estimator, X_test, y_test, class_labels_lists, descriptive_text):
    """
    Calls predict on an estimator (i.e. model_estimator) like a fit pipeline oject, displays and saves common classification performance metrics
    To_do: implement boolean to run silently; add more options for graphing (e.g. labelling classes)

    Parameters
    ----------
    model_estimator: A fit model
    X_test (pandas.core.frame.DataFrame): Test data for evaluating model performance
    y_test (pandas.core.frame.DataFrame): Test labels for evaluating model performance
    class_labels_lists (list of lists): [[L1],[L2]]
        L1: array-like of shape (n_classes,)
                List of labels to index the matrix. This may be used to reorder or
                select a subset of labels. If `None` is given, those that appear at
                least once in `y_true` or `y_pred` are used in sorted order.
        L2: display_labels : array-like of shape (n_classes,)
                Target names used for plotting. By default, `labels` will be used if
                it is defined, otherwise the unique labels of `y_true` and `y_pred`
                will be used.
    decriptive_text (str): Optional descriptive text to add to graph titles
    bool_print -- not implemented yet

    Returns
    -------
    model_prediction: a numpy array generated by "predict"
    report: a classification report
    cm: a confusion matrix plot
    
    
    """
    # Fit model
    model_prediction = model_estimator.predict(X_test)
    
    # Build, display, and save classification report
    report = classification_report(y_test, model_prediction)
    print(report)
    
    # Build, display, and save classification report
    cm = plot_confusion_matrix(model_estimator, X_test, y_test, labels=class_labels_lists[0], display_labels=class_labels_lists[1],
                    cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    cm.ax_.set_title("Confusion Matrix: " + descriptive_text)
    plt.show()
    return model_prediction, report, cm

Optimize imputation: Choose the correct k for KNN

In[33]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedStratifiedKFold
from numpy import mean
from numpy import std
from matplotlib import pyplot
In[34]:
# Find the best k in KNN. Note that lower k will have more noise and higher k will approximate
# just imputing with mean.
# Modified from https://machinelearningmastery.com/knn-imputation-for-missing-values-in-machine-learning/
results = list()
ks = [str(i) for i in [1,3,5,7,9,11,311]]
for k in ks:
    # create the pipeline
    pl_steps = [('KNN imputer', KNNImputer(n_neighbors=int(k),weights='distance')),
                ('robust scaler', RobustScaler()),
                ('lr', LogisticRegression(random_state=52))]
    KNN_pipeline = Pipeline(pl_steps)
    # evaluate the model using cross-validation
    cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=5, random_state=99)
    scores = cross_val_score(KNN_pipeline, X_train, y_train, scoring='recall', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
    # store results
    results.append(scores)
    print('>%s %.3f (%.3f)' % (k, mean(scores), std(scores)))

>1 0.943 (0.050)
>3 0.944 (0.050)
>5 0.944 (0.049)
>7 0.944 (0.049)
>9 0.944 (0.049)
>11 0.944 (0.049)
>311 0.943 (0.048)
In[35]:
# plot model performance for comparison
pyplot.boxplot(results, labels=ks, showmeans=True)
pyplot.show()

It seems like the size of k doesn't have a big impact on model performance. I wonder if KNNImputation is actually any better than a more naive approach like using the mean....based on the above results probably only slightly and might not be robustly different. I will test if KNNImputation is actually any better than a more naive approach next.

Random Forest with hyperparameter search

In[43]:
# Create the pipeline
rf_pl_steps = [('KNN imputer', KNNImputer(n_neighbors=3, weights='distance')),
                ('robust scaler', RobustScaler()),
                ('rf', RandomForestClassifier(random_state=52))]
rf_pipeline = Pipeline(rf_pl_steps)
In[44]:
# Create hyperparameter search space

# np.linspace returns evenly spaced numbers over a specified interval to search number of trees in the forest
# According to the RandomizedSearchCV docs "It is highly recommended to use continuous distributions for continuous parameters."
# To-do: replace below search space with distributions
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 20, stop = 200, num = 10)]
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['log2', 'sqrt'] # Note that in this instance since features are small they end up being very similar
# Maximum depth of the tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(1, 45, num = 11)]
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [3, 5, 10, 15]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'rf__n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'rf__max_features': max_features,
               'rf__max_depth': max_depth,
               'rf__min_samples_split': min_samples_split}
pprint(random_grid)

Check model performance with less features (could do RFE but lets start simply)

Create a class to choose just the columns that I'm interested in so that I can wrap it in a pipeline

In[64]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

In[65]:
# Custom Transformer that extracts columns passed as argument 
class FeatureChooser(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    '''A custom transformer that allows a subset of columns to be passed in a sklearn Pipeline'''
     
    def __init__(self, feature_names):
        '''Initialize'''
        self.feature_names = feature_names 
    
    def fit(self, X, y = None):
        '''Fit to data method'''
        return self 
    
    def transform(self, X, y = None):
        '''Applies transform to data'''
        return X[self.feature_names]
